- $P(RW) = P(R \text{ from male}) \times P(W \text{ from female}) = 0.5 \times 0.5 = 0.25$
- $P(WR) = P(W \text{ from male}) \times P(R \text{ from female}) = 0.5 \times 0.5 = 0.25$
- $P(WW) = P(W \text{ from male}) \times P(W \text{ from female}) = 0.5 \times 0.5 = 0.25$
So, $P(RR) = 0.25$, $P(RW) = 0.25$, $P(WR) = 0.25$, and $P(WW) = 0.25$.

## Step 3: Determine the probability that an offspring has white eyes.
An offspring will have white eyes if it has either $WW$ or $RW$ or $WR$ genotype. Thus, $P(\text{white eyes}) = P(WW) + P(RW) + P(WR) = 0.25 + 0.25 + 0.25 = 0.75$.

## Step 4: Calculate the conditional probability that an offspring has two white alleles given that its eyes are white.
The conditional probability of having $WW$ given white eyes is calculated using the formula $P(WW | \text{white eyes}) = \frac{P(WW)}{P(\text{white eyes})}$. We know $P(WW) = 0.25$ and $P(\text{white eyes}) = 0.75$.

## Step 5: Perform the calculation for the conditional probability.
$P(WW | \text{white eyes}) = \frac{0.25}{0.75} = 0.3333...$

